<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910221-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>910221-0010.</DOCID><HL>   GE, Yokogawa Venture   Faces Bribery Allegations</HL><DATE>02/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><CO>   GE JAPAN J.YHE</CO><IN>MEDICAL SUPPLIES (MDS)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- General Electric Co.'s sales of medical equipmentin Japan appear threatened by bribery allegations against ajoint venture selling the American company's products.   The venture, Yokogawa Medical Systems Ltd., said it hasbeen told by customers that the Japanese government ordereduniversities and hospitals this week to halt business withthe venture, which is 75%-owned by GE. The rest is owned byYokogawa Electric.</LP><TEXT>   Yokogawa Medical, established in 1982, had sales of 52.3billion yen ($398.1 million) in the year ended Nov. 19, 1989,most of which involved diagnostic imaging equipment. Thecompany has about a 10% market share, according to industryestimates. The company is neck-and-neck with industry leaderToshiba in the more specialized field of magnetic resonanceimaging.   The government order followed arrests last week of twoYokogawa Medical employees on charges that they bribeduniversity professors to get them to buy GE-made equipment. Auniversity professor at a hospital near Tokyo was alsoarrested, and Japanese news reports said it was for accepting400,000 yen in travelers checks from Yokogawa Medical forhelping the company win a 230 million yen contract last yearto sell an X-ray scanner.   GE officials in Tokyo were not immediately available forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>